<h2 id="case-buying-guide">Case Buying Guide</h2>

<p><img class="lazyload img-right img-small" alt="carbide air 540" data-src="/img/case/carbide-air-540.png" /></p>

<p>If you‚Äôre interested in building a gaming PC, it is imperative that you choose the <a href="https://www.computercaselab.com/what-makes-a-computer-case-the-best-for-gaming/" target="_blank">right case</a>. Of course, that‚Äôs easier said than done.</p>

<p>In an effort to aid those new to building gaming computers, I‚Äôve created this guide to help you understand everything you need to know when it comes to selecting the best ATX case.</p>

<p><strong>So, what‚Äôs the deal with ATX, micro-ATX, and mini-ITX?</strong></p>

<p>The names stem from motherboard size categories. Motherboards are grouped into these three categories.</p>

<p>ATX is the largest, micro-ATX is a bit smaller, and mini-ITX is the smallest.</p>

<p>At the moment, full-sized ATX cases are the most popular form factor for a variety of reasons.</p>

<p>ATX motherboards are 12 √ó 9.6 inches (305 √ó 244 mm). ATX cases are usually also compatible with micro-ATX motherboards, which are 9.6 √ó 9.6 inches (244 √ó 244 mm).</p>

<p>Lastly, mini-ITX motherboards are 6.7 √ó 6.7 inches (170 x 170 mm), making them the smallest of the three form-factors.</p>

<p>Since cases are responsible for housing motherboards, cases are categorized in the same manner (ATX, micro-ATX, etc.)</p>

<p>It‚Äôs always important to ensure that the case you want is compatible with your motherboard‚Äôs form factor.</p>

<h2 id="a-great-case-is">A Great Case Is‚Ä¶</h2>

<p><strong>1.</strong> A great gaming case is strong. Avoid cases constructed with flimsy plastic ‚Äì after all, your case is supposed to protect your parts and keep them from breaking, right?</p>

<p>A few plastic parts here and there are okay and most cases have some plastic. However, ensure the plastic is strong and of high quality before risking your expensive components.</p>

<p><strong>2.</strong> A great gaming case has fantastic <a href="/cable-management/">airflow</a>. If your case doesn‚Äôt have good airflow, your PC could overheat and shut down.</p>

<p>Despite being able to handle high temperatures, your parts can become damaged if they are too hot. Whether you‚Äôre using 80mm, 120mm, or 140mm case fans, <em>airflow is incredibly important!</em></p>

<p>You may find this PC airflow guide helpful:</p>

<div class="vid-container">
<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/sh6F2eccMec" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; encrypted-media" allowfullscreen=""></iframe>
</div>

<p><strong>3.</strong> A great gaming case has room for plenty of <em>quiet</em> case fans! This goes hand-in-hand with airflow. If your case doesn‚Äôt have space to add case fans, it‚Äôs a no go.</p>

<p><img class="lazyload img-right img-small" alt="Thermaltake Core G3" data-src="/img/case/thermaltake-core-g3.jpg" /></p>

<p>Most gaming cases ship with fans included ‚Äì many of them have cool looking LEDs too.</p>

<p>But before you‚Äôre fooled by fancy lights, it‚Äôs important to make sure your fans are quiet.</p>

<p>Noisy fans can be especially annoying if you‚Äôre sensitive to noise.</p>

<p><strong>4.</strong> A great gaming case has enough room for your components! This may seem obvious, but some cases don‚Äôt have enough room for CPU coolers and graphics cards.</p>

<p>For example, the first time I built a gaming PC, the hard drive bays in my case got in the way of my graphics card!</p>

<p><strong>5.</strong> A great gaming case has good cable management options. This means there is plenty of space for your cables, and they can be run throughout the case in a neat and orderly fashion.</p>

<p>Instead of bundling them up inside the case ‚Äì which is both ugly and bad for airflow ‚Äì you can run your cables in the back.</p>

<p>This keeps your case looking clean and promotes good airflow.</p>

<p>Before you pull the trigger on the case of your dreams, make sure that:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Your graphics card will fit inside the case</li>
  <li>Your CPU cooler will fit inside the case</li>
  <li>Your case has enough hard drive bays</li>
</ul>

<p>Otherwise, you‚Äôll be quite disappointed!</p>

<h2 id="do-you-need-a-gaming-case">Do You Need a ‚ÄòGaming‚Äô Case?</h2>

<p>Many companies advertise their cases as ‚Äúgaming cases‚Äù. Just because a case is outfitted with cool LED lights does not necessarily make it a gaming case.</p>

<p>Most uneducated customers will buy a case simply for its looks, without really considering the factors mentioned above.</p>

<p>It is more important to find a functional case that provides good airflow and cable management. A good case must also be sturdy and cost effective.</p>

<p>Sure, a good looking case is always nice, but it is <em>not</em> necessary. If you‚Äôre on a budget, especially a budget below $500, don‚Äôt spend more than $50 on your case.</p>

<p>In fact, I‚Äôd recommend spending $40 or less. For more information on <a href="/pc-cases/">choosing the best case for your PC</a>, check out our complete guide.</p>

